ISeries<java.lang.Object[][]>
public class LabeledNumberSeries
extends AbstractSeries<java.lang.Object[][]>

Implementation of AbstractSeries which represents an array of Label/Y-Pairs to be plotted on the chart. The corresponding X-Values will be automatically calculated by Highcharts, counting from 0 on.

For example: If you set the Y-Values to new Integer[]{2,6,9}, Highcharts will plot the points (0/2), (1/6) and (2/9).

The label will be used as a caption for the actual point on the chart.

For more information read href="http://www.highcharts.com/ref/#series.

Method Detail

setData

public LabeledNumberSeries setData(java.lang.Object[][] pData)
Sets a two-dimensional array of Label/Y-Pairs to be plotted on the chart. The corresponding X-Values will be automatically calculated by Highcharts, counting from 0 on.

The second dimension of the array must have the length of 2, to represent Label/Y pairs. Additionally the first field of the second dimension must be a String value representing the label. The second field must be an instance of Number. If that is not the case, an InvalidParameterException will be thrown.

Parameters:
pData - a two-dimensional array of Label/Y-Pairs
Returns:
this object for convenient chaining, not a copy
Throws:
java.security.InvalidParameterException
See Also:
LabeledNumberSeries

setData

public LabeledNumberSeries setData(java.lang.String[] pLabels,
                                   java.lang.Number[] pYValues)
Sets two arrays to represent labels and Y values for coordinates to be plotted on the chart. Both array must have the same length or an IllegalArgumentException will be thrown. Every y-Value will be paired with a label, stored at the same array index. The corresponding X-Values will be automatically calculated by Highcharts, counting from 0 on.

Parameters:
pLabels - an array representing the labels
pYValues - an array representing the Y-Values
Returns:
this object for convenient chaining, not a copy

Sets two arrays to represent Labels and Y values for coordinates to be plotted on the chart. Both arrays must have the same length or an IllegalArgumentException will be thrown. Every X-Value will be paired with a label, stored at the same array index. The corresponding X-Values will be automatically calculated by Highcharts, counting from 0 on.
